INTRODUCTION
The rapid expansion of digital commerce has transformed how consumers discover, evaluate, and purchase products. Within this ecosystem, recommender systems have emerged as a central mechanism for personalizing user experiences and guiding purchasing decisions. E-commerce platforms such as Amazon and Flipkart deploy recommendation algorithms to filter vast product catalogs and present users with tailored suggestions based on historical interactions.
Despite significant advancements in recommendation techniques, existing systems are predominantly grounded in structured behavioral data such as clicks, ratings, and purchase history. While effective in identifying patterns of past behavior, these systems often fail to capture the underlying motivations that drive user decisions. In particular, they overlook emotional cues embedded in user-generated textual content, including reviews, feedback, and comments. These textual signals reflect subjective experiences and perceptions that cannot be fully represented through numerical ratings alone.
Natural Language Processing (NLP) has made substantial progress in extracting meaning from unstructured text, particularly through the development of encoding techniques that transform textual data into dense vector representations. These encoders are capable of capturing contextual and semantic nuances, including sentiment and emotional tone. However, in practical implementations, such capabilities are rarely integrated into recommendation pipelines in a meaningful way.
This study addresses this gap by proposing an emotion-aware recommender system tailored to e-commerce environments. The system incorporates NLP-based encoding techniques to extract emotional signals from textual data and integrates these signals with behavioral features within a unified modeling framework. The objective is to evaluate whether this integration leads to measurable improvements in recommendation relevance, user engagement, and purchase intention.
By bridging the gap between behavioral analytics and emotional intelligence, this research contributes to a more comprehensive understanding of user decision-making in digital commerce and offers practical insights for enhancing personalization strategies.

SCOPE AND OBJECTIVES
Research Problems and Questions
The central research problem guiding this study is the limited ability of traditional recommender systems to incorporate emotional context into their predictive processes. While users frequently express their experiences and preferences through textual content, this information remains underutilized in recommendation models. As a result, recommendations may be accurate in a historical sense but misaligned with the user’s current mindset or intent.
To address this issue, the study is structured around the following research questions:

Research Question 1
Does the integration of NLP-based emotional embeddings into recommender systems lead to a statistically significant improvement in user engagement compared to traditional behavior-based recommendation models?

Research Question 2
To what extent does an emotion-aware recommender system enhance the perceived relevance of product recommendations from the user’s perspective?

Research Question 3
What is the effect of emotion-aware recommendations on user purchase intention within an e-commerce context?

Research Question 4
Do advanced encoding techniques, particularly transformer-based models, provide superior performance in capturing emotional signals compared to traditional sentiment analysis methods when applied to recommendation systems?

Sample Size Calculation
The study adopts a quantitative experimental design, requiring an appropriate sample size to ensure statistical validity and reliability of results. The sample size is determined using power analysis, which accounts for the probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis.
Assuming a confidence level of 95 percent, a statistical power of 0.80, and a medium effect size, the required sample size for each experimental group is approximately 64 participants. Given that the study involves a comparison between a control group (traditional recommender system) and a treatment group (emotion-aware recommender system), the total minimum sample size is estimated at 128 participants.
To account for potential data loss due to incomplete responses or inconsistencies, the study will target a sample size in the range of 150 to 200 participants. This range ensures sufficient statistical power for hypothesis testing, including t-tests and regression analysis, while maintaining diversity in the findings.

DATA DESCRIPTION

Data Sources
The study utilizes a combination of secondary and primary data sources to construct a comprehensive dataset that captures both behavioral and emotional dimensions of user interaction.
Product-related data, including item descriptions, categories, and metadata, will be obtained through APIs such as the Amazon Product Advertising API and the Fake Store API. These sources provide structured information necessary for building the recommendation framework.
User-generated textual data, including reviews and informal expressions of opinion, will be collected from platforms such as the Reddit API and the X (formerly known as Twitter). These sources offer rich linguistic data that can be analyzed to extract emotional signals.
In addition, primary data will be collected through structured surveys designed to capture user perceptions of recommendation relevance, engagement levels, and purchase intention. This component allows for direct measurement of business-oriented outcomes that cannot be inferred solely from behavioral logs.

Data Dictionary
The dataset will include both structured and unstructured variables. Key variables are defined as follows:
•	user_id: Unique identifier assigned to each participant 
•	product_id: Identifier for each product 
•	rating: Numerical rating provided by the user 
•	review_text: Textual content expressing user opinion 
•	sentiment_score: Quantified emotional polarity derived from text 
•	embedding_vector: Encoded representation of textual data 
•	engagement_score: Measure of user interaction with recommendations 
•	purchase_intention: Likert-scale measure indicating likelihood of purchase 
These variables collectively support the integration of behavioral and emotional features within the modeling framework.

GitHub Repository
To ensure transparency and reproducibility, all data processing steps, modeling procedures, and evaluation scripts will be maintained in a publicly accessible GitHub repository. The repository will include:
•	raw and processed datasets 
•	scripts for data cleaning and preprocessing 
•	implementation of the NLP pipeline 
•	recommender system models 
•	evaluation and visualization outputs

Dataset Structure and Documentation
The dataset will be organized into multiple directories corresponding to raw data, processed data, and model outputs. Each component will be documented with clear descriptions, and relevant screenshots will be included in the final report. Where necessary, directory structures will be illustrated to facilitate understanding of data flow within the system.

ANALYTIC APPROACH
Techniques and Hypotheses
The study adopts a comparative analytical approach, evaluating the performance of a traditional recommender system against an emotion-aware model.

Research Question 1
The first analysis examines whether emotional embeddings improve user engagement.
•	Null Hypothesis: The inclusion of emotional features does not significantly affect user engagement 
•	Alternative Hypothesis: The inclusion of emotional features leads to a significant increase in user engagement 
This will be tested using t-tests and regression models, comparing interaction metrics between the control and treatment groups.

Research Question 2
The second analysis evaluates perceived relevance.
•	Null Hypothesis: There is no difference in perceived relevance between the two systems 
•	Alternative Hypothesis: The emotion-aware system produces higher perceived relevance 
This will be assessed using Likert-scale responses and analyzed through statistical comparison techniques.

Research Question 3
The third analysis focuses on purchase intention.
•	Null Hypothesis: Emotional context does not influence purchase intention 
•	Alternative Hypothesis: Emotion-aware recommendations increase purchase intention 
Logistic regression and correlation analysis will be used to evaluate this relationship.

Research Question 4
The fourth analysis compares encoding techniques.
•	Null Hypothesis: There is no difference between encoding approaches 
•	Alternative Hypothesis: Transformer-based encoders outperform traditional sentiment methods 

Model performance will be compared using recommendation metrics.

EVALUATION METRICS
The effectiveness of the models will be assessed using both technical and business-oriented metrics.
Precision@K measures the proportion of relevant items among the top recommendations. 
Recall@K evaluates the ability of the system to retrieve all relevant items. 
Normalized Discounted Cumulative Gain (NDCG) assesses the ranking quality of recommendations.
In addition to these, engagement rate is calculated as the ratio of user interactions to total recommendations presented. Purchase intention is measured using averaged Likert-scale responses.
Statistical significance will be evaluated using p-values, with a threshold of 0.05 indicating meaningful differences between models.

RECOMMENDATION AND APPLICATION
The findings of this research are intended to support decision-making in e-commerce environments. The primary users of the proposed system include digital commerce organizations, recommendation system developers, and marketing strategists.
By integrating emotional intelligence into recommendation processes, businesses can enhance the relevance of product suggestions and improve user experience. This has direct implications for customer satisfaction, retention, and conversion rates.
The system also provides a foundation for more adaptive and context-aware personalization strategies. Instead of relying solely on historical data, organizations can respond dynamically to user sentiment, enabling more responsive and intuitive interactions.

